I normally will tip in cash on my way out of a bar or venue based on my experience. I tipped a quarter for my beer on my card. For an 8 dollar beer, I tip change (sometimes not at all). But I usually tip for the service and hospitality separately. The man that saw my quarter tip, began to scoff and mock me AS I WAS SITTING in the bar.

Look I know a quarter sucks, but I tip out of the kindness and generosity of my heart and pouring a pint isnt an automatic 5 dollar tip. I was planning on spending time there and possibly drinking more.  But this place was absolutely awful.

Expect to tip well up front if you want people to be kind to you. Sad

This is nothing against the bartenders, wait staff, or general team at Crown Station, who I have no doubt perform an excellent job based on the glowing reviews. However, management failed to uphold its duties as an event venue, cancelling our wedding party six days prior to the event with the justification that “another event had to reschedule for the same day and they could not cancel.” In other words, they considered that event more important than an already scheduled special occasion.

My significant other and I were able to find an alternative venue, yet we are left to contact nearly 130 guests of the change at the last minute. It’s clear from management’s lack of consideration and empathy of the situation that I am leery of requesting their services in the future despite such strong service from the rest of the team. The only thing preventing this from being a 1 star review was the fact that the initial payment was refunded, but I am saddened to see that they chose profits over people.

I do not recommend.

reviews_data.review_text:
*UPDATE* 11/13/22
Visited the establishment again for an event on 11/11/22.
I never heard back from the manager about being overcharged from the previous visit.

To add insult to injury, come to find out I was being charged for soft drinks and they were being given out for free to others this whole time. So that's not very cool.

After updating my review a few weeks ago, I was prepared to change my rating based on the owner's communication with me. There was none.

So at this time, I can only give 1 star. I would give zero.

I won't be recommending this establishment.
Nor partaking at any special events where I feel like people are being ripped off.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
I was there for happy hour. I was charged $22.95 for 1 diet Pepsi and a well shot of tequila. The bartender apologized for the price. Which she shouldn't had, it is EXTREMELY overpriced and will not be partaking in the consumption of goods from this business in the future.

Update, the owners never reached out to me even though they publicly stated in their reply to my review that they would. I was charged, they have collected their money and they have offered NO reason on why a well shot of tequila and a diet Pepsi were over $22.00.

Buyer beware. I will not be spending any money this establishment. Taking 5 days to respond for a follow up is unacceptable. I hope this review helps people make better decisions about future purchases at your establishment.
reviews_data.owner_answer: We appreciate your feedback. Very sorry to hear you had a bad experience at our bar. We agree, those prices do not seem correct. I will look into this and reply back.

reviews_data.owner_answer: Sorry that this impacted your night. This is a requirement set in place by the North Carolina. If a venue servers alcohol but does not serve food, they are defacto a private club. Unfortunately, this requires a fee for membership for entry. Your membership is saved into a system and is kept on record. You only pay this once. We're sorry this soured your experience, but this is NC law and we have to comply.

reviews_data.review_text: Upon entry, I was immediately put off by the doorman tacking on an additional membership fee but no where is it posted that this is a private club.  Nevermind!
reviews_data.owner_answer: Sorry about that Jason, but this is a requirement of the state. As Crown Station does not sell food, but does sell alcohol it is a defacto private club. North Carolina law requires that patrons are paid members, this is where the dollar membership fee comes from. I apologize that this soured your reputation of us, but we have to comply to North Carolina law.

This is nothing against the bartenders, wait staff, or general team at Crown Station, who I have no doubt perform an excellent job based on the glowing reviews. However, management failed to uphold its duties as an event venue, cancelling our wedding party six days prior to the event with the justification that “another event had to reschedule for the same day and they could not cancel.” In other words, they considered that event more important than an already scheduled special occasion.

My significant other and I were able to find an alternative venue, yet we are left to contact nearly 130 guests of the change at the last minute. It’s clear from management’s lack of consideration and empathy of the situation that I am leery of requesting their services in the future despite such strong service from the rest of the team. The only thing preventing this from being a 1 star review was the fact that the initial payment was refunded, but I am saddened to see that they chose profits over people.

Went for an event tonight and an additional $1 was tacked onto the entry fee. They could at least have mentioned this on the event flyer OR have it listed on their Facebook page or webpage that this is a private club. There is no membership cards or accounts so is that an extra $1 every time? Why not simply incorporate it into the entry fee so there are no surprises? Horrible nickel and diming. Will not be back. :(
reviews_data.owner_answer: Sorry that this impacted your night. This is a requirement set in place by the North Carolina. If a venue servers alcohol but does not serve food, they are defacto a private club. Unfortunately, this requires a fee for membership for entry. Your membership is saved into a system and is kept on record. You only pay this once. We're sorry this soured your experience, but this is NC law and we have to comply.

reviews_data.review_text: Upon entry, I was immediately put off by the doorman tacking on an additional membership fee but no where is it posted that this is a private club.  Nevermind!
reviews_data.owner_answer: Sorry about that Jason, but this is a requirement of the state. As Crown Station does not sell food, but does sell alcohol it is a defacto private club. North Carolina law requires that patrons are paid members, this is where the dollar membership fee comes from. I apologize that this soured your reputation of us, but we have to comply to North Carolina law.
